To solve this, we first condense the absolute value inequality to remove the absolute.
\begin{align*} -16 & \le \lvert2x+7\rvert \le 16 \\ -16 & \le 2x+7 \le 16 \\ 12 & \le 2x \le 9  \\ 6 & \le x \le 4.5 \end{align*}
Since $x$ needs to be the least integer value, our answer is $\boxed{4}$.  <answer>4</answer>

Let $z = a + bi$, where $a$ and $b$ are real numbers. The given conditions can be rewritten as:
\begin{align*}
\left| \frac{(a - 4) + bi}{(a - 8) + bi} \right| &= 1, \\
\left| \frac{(a - 12) + bi}{(a - 8i) + bi} \right| &= \frac{5}{3}.
\end{align*}
Using the definition of the absolute value of a complex number, we have:
\begin{align*}
\sqrt{\frac{(a - 4)^2 + b^2}{(a - 8)^2 + b^2}} &= 1, \\
\sqrt{\frac{(a - 12)^2 + b^2}{(a - 8)^2 + b^2}} &= \frac{5}{3}.
\end{align*}
Squaring both sides of the equations, we obtain:
\begin{align*}
\frac{(a - 4)^2 + b^2}{(a - 8)^2 + b^2} &= 1, \\
\frac{(a - 12)^2 + b^2}{(a - 8)^2 + b^2} &= \frac{25}{9}.
\end{align*}
Solving these equations, we find that $a = 6 \pm 2\sqrt{2}$ and $b = 0$.
</think>
<answer>Thus, the complex numbers $z$ that satisfy the given conditions are $z = 6 + 2\sqrt{2}i$ and $z = 6 - 2\sqrt{2}i$.</answer>

